{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510467","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510467"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:30:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:30:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11564"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11564","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11564"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.06,0.03,0.07,0.78]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4193"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103593"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4193","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4193"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11564"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86010"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2166"},{"type":"tags","id":"4378"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5423"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7246"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39833"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43251"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103593"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old woman presents to the emergency department with vaginal bleeding at 30 weeks gestation. She is G4P2 with one spontaneous vaginal delivery at 40 weeks followed by a caesarian section at term for failure to progress. So far, this pregnancy has been uncomplicated with morphology scan revealing an anterior placenta that is low lying near the internal os.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient describes one episode of bright red painless bleeding (one teaspoon) earlier the same day. She otherwise feels well and foetal movements are present. On examination she is haemodynamically stable and the abdomen is soft and non-tender. Speculum reveals cervix homogenous in colour with a closed os. CTG shows no signs of fetal distress.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of the bleeding?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Placenta accreta","Vasa previa","Placental abruption","Cervical ectropion","Placenta previa"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAntepartum haemorrhage (APH) is defined as bleeding in pregnancy after 20 weeks gestational age and prior to labour. Categorising APH by location can be useful in considering a broad range of differentials (e.g. placental, cervical, vaginal, vulval, non-genital). Important features on assessment include the presence of pain, maternal haemodynamic instability and fetal distress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommon causes of painless APH without haemodynamic or fetal compromise include cervical ectropion and \u003Cstrong\u003Eplacenta previa\u003C/strong\u003E. Placenta previa is typically found on serial ultrasound after a low-lying placenta is detected at morphology scan. Otherwise, patients may present with vaginal bleeding after 27 weeks when the placental position changes with the formation of the lower uterine segment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECervical ectropion\u003C/strong\u003E is characterised by eversion and then metaplasia of columnar epithelium of the endocervix to squamous cell ectocervix when exposed to the acidic environment of the vagina. This eversion of the endocervical epithelium onto the ectocervix occurs under the influence of oestrogen (e.g. pregnancy, puberty, OCP) and may be asymptomatic or cause vaginal spotting and post-coital bleeding. Cervical ectropion can be excluded in this case given the absence of a sharply demarcated erythematous area surrounding the cervical os. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVasa previa \u003C/strong\u003Eis when the fetal vessels traverse the internal os. It may occur alongside placenta previa but causes painless bleeding after rupture of membranes and results in fetal distress.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlacental abruption \u003C/strong\u003Eis an important differential for antepartum haemorrhage and an obstetric emergency. It is associated with pain, fetal distress and, depending on the degree of blood loss, maternal haemodynamic instability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAbnormal placental attachment including \u003Cstrong\u003Eplacenta accreta \u003C/strong\u003Eis typically a cause of postpartum haemorrhage (PPH). Placenta accreta describes the situation where the placenta extends deeply in to the uterus and can remain embedded (total or in part) after delivery. It should be suspected following vaginal delivery if there is difficulty delivering the placenta and/or absent segments.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Placenta previa is a cause of painless APH"],"references":["Arulkumaran, Sabaratnam and others (eds), Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology (Oxford, 2020; online edn, Oxford Academic, 1 Jan. 2020).","Prendiville W, Sankaranarayanan R. Colposcopy and Treatment of Cervical Precancer. Lyon (FR): International Agency for Research on Cancer; 2017. (IARC Technical Report, No. 45.) Chapter 2., Anatomy of the uterine cervix and the transformation zone. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK568392/","Anderson-Bagga FM, Sze A. Placenta Previa. [Updated 2023 Jun 12]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539818/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86010"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11564"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86010"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-24T12:05:36+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-27T10:25:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4193"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103593"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationshi